Requirements:
In addition to the general requirements of the university, specific requirements for admission to classified graduate status are:

1. A minimum of 24 units of upper-division coursework in Kinesiology or a related field;
2. A course in introductory statistics;
3. A course in either exercise physiology or biomechanics;
4. One of the following:
    a. A minimum of a 3.0 GPA in the last 60 semester units (90 quarter units) of coursework;
    b. A minimum score on the Graduate Record Examination (GRE): 150 on the verbal section, 141 on the quantitative section, and 3.5 on the analytical writing section; or
    c. A master’s degree in a related field from an accredited university.
5. Submission of the following to the department Graduate Coordinator:
    a. Three letters of recommendation from individuals who can speak to the applicant’s academic and professional potential;
    b. A 500-word statement of purpose describing the applicant’s motivation and goals for pursuing the M.A. in Kinesiology, option in Coaching and Student-Athlete Development at CSULB; and
    c. A professional résumé highlighting the applicant’s experience in coaching, athletic administration, and/or student-athlete development.
6. A personal interview with the CSAD faculty.

To be considered for admission to the Master of Arts Degree in Kinesiology, a student must:
1. A baccalaureate degree from an accredited institution with a major in Kinesiology or an equivalent degree with an appropriate background in the field as determined by the graduate committee;
2. Be in good academic standing at the last college or university attended;
3. A grade point average (GPA) of 3.0 or better in the last 60 semester units (90 quarter units) of upper-division coursework and a 3.0 GPA in all Kinesiology coursework;
4. Three letters of recommendation from persons who have knowledge of the applicant’s academic and professional potential;
5. A written statement of purpose that demonstrates the applicant’s interest and preparation for graduate study in the chosen option;
6. A sample of the applicant’s scholarly writing (e.g., a paper from a previous course);
7. A personal interview with the graduate coordinator and/or option faculty.

In addition to the general requirements of the university, specific requirements for admission to classified graduate status are:
1. A Bachelor of Arts degree with a major in Art, with a specialization in Art History, or a baccalaureate degree with a minimum of 24 upper-division units in Art History, or their equivalent, acceptable to the Art History Admissions Committee;
2. A scholarship average of 3.0 ("B") or better in all upper-division art history courses and an overall scholarship average of 3.0 or better in the last 60 semester (90 quarter) units;
3. Submission of a statement of purpose of 500-1,000 words describing the applicant’s preparation for the program, goals in the program, and professional objectives;
4. Submission of a writing sample: a research paper of at least five pages (double-spaced, 12-point font), demonstrating the applicant’s ability to write a scholarly paper on an art historical topic. The writing sample should have a clear thesis, a logical development, and a conclusion. It should follow an accepted format (MLA, Chicago, etc.) for notes and bibliography;
5. Submission of a resume listing relevant academic and professional experience;
6. Submission of at least two letters of recommendation from professors or other qualified individuals.

In addition to the general requirements of the university, specific requirements for admission to classified graduate status are:
1. Have a minimum 3.0 GPA for the last 60 semester (or 90 quarter) units of undergraduate coursework.
2. Hold a baccalaureate degree with a major in dance from an accredited institution or the equivalent in professional experience.
3. Submit the following materials directly to the Department of Dance:
    a. A curriculum vitae (CV) or professional resume;
    b. A 1000-word statement of purpose describing the applicant’s background and reasons for pursuing graduate study in dance;
    c. A scholarly writing sample (5-10 pages) in English that demonstrates graduate-level research, analysis, and writing skills;
    d. A choreography portfolio, submitted via a video link, consisting of one or two complete works of the applicant’s original choreography, totaling no more than 15 minutes in length.
    e. Three confidential letters of recommendation from persons who are in a position to comment on the applicant’s potential for success in a graduate-level dance program.
4. Complete an interview/audition.

To be considered for admission to CSULB, you must meet the following minimum requirements: 
1. Be a high school graduate or equivalent; 
2. Complete the 15-unit comprehensive “A-G” pattern of college preparatory courses; 
3. Earn a qualifying “A-G” grade point average (GPA). 

CSULB is impacted for all undergraduate programs, which means we receive more qualified applications than we can accommodate. Therefore, meeting the minimum CSU requirements does not guarantee admission. Admission is competitive and based on the academic record and preparation of the applicants for that term.
